Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Business Designer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-7)

Numbering schemes can be defined and used in Business Designer from version 6.2 on. The numbering schemes can be found in the left toolbar under "Other". With a numbering scheme the automated enumeration and numbering of e.g. chapters, images, tables or appendix can be achieved. Four predefined default schemas (chapter, figure, table and appendix) are provided in the templates for simplified operation. The standard schemas can also be adapted. The schemas can be set on block level in the editor.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

You can add any number of numbering schemes locally or from external resources. Move the mouse cursor over the scheme name to change the name or delete the scheme via the black menu.

On the right side you can edit the attributes of the scheme. The following attributes are available:

**Attribute**

**Description**

Name

Unique name to identify the scheme in the template

Value

Initial value of numbering

Number Format

decimal (1,2,3), decimal-leading-zero (01,02,03),lower-alpha (a,b,c), upper- alpha (A,B,C), lower-roman (i,ii,iii), upper- roman (I,II,III)

Prefix

A value inserted before the number (e.g. "chapter") Spaces are also respected

Suffix

A value inserted after the number (e.g. a bracket ")")

Separator

A value to be displayed after each numbering level. (e.g. "." so that at decimal will be displayed like 1.1 or 1.1.1 and so on).

Left padding

Distance kept before the numbering on the left side (e.g. 10mm).

Right padding

Distance which is kept after the numbering on the right side (e.g. 10mm)

**Attribute**

**Description**

Width

Total width of the whole numbering element (e.g. 50mm). Attention: the distance left and right should not exceed the total width.

After defining the scheme, it can be used on block level in the editor. To do so, select the desired block and in the right-hand area under Styles &amp; Properties, *Numbering *select the desired scheme under *Name*. The numbered element can also be referenced, a unique ID must be set in the *ID *attribute. With the attribute *Level *the numbering level can be determined (e.g. 1,2,3.. etc). For example 1 = 1, 2 = 1.1, 3 = 1.1.1 and so on. If the field is left empty, the system starts at 1 or depending on the format with 01, a, A, i or I.

In the design view, the set schemas are displayed in blue:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Numbering Reference
You can find the element *Numbering reference *in the palette which is used for references within a template.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Drag the element to the desired location in the template and then enter the ID of the numbered element you want to reference under Styles &amp; Settings, Numbering, *Reference ID*. You can choose whether the reference should be shown with the number, the text or the page number of the element and you can create a link so the user is able to get to the desired position in the rendered document (works like an anchor). Additionally, you can select if the position should be kept and you can set the width of the element. The reference automatically adjusts when changes are made (as long as the ID remains the same).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Table of Contents
You can find the element *Table of Contents *in the palette, with which you can create table of contents automatically. Drag the element to the desired position in the template and select the name of the scheme from which you want to create the table of contents under Styles &amp; Properties in the Numbering area. The table of contents will be displayed as a placeholder and it will be generated automatically during rendering.

## Numbering Improvement
With 6.4 Version the Numbering scheme is supported in Composer and MS Word documents.
